// LA-30 doc 5 §2 C3, worker variant: a spawned body's own inner await
// drains — the promise it awaits is created and settled entirely INSIDE the
// worker body (never referenced from the spawner's side), so this never trips
// A-1's spawn-body-Promise reject (bug #35, reject route A — see
// spawn_global_promise_rejected.lev). Byte-identical on oracle/IR/LLVM.
//
// Live since the M5 flip (doc 2 §7 — no new plumbing): the inner await
// throws C3's RuntimeException *inside* the body; `spawn`'s existing
// try/catch converts it into a rejection; `await w` rethrows it at the
// spawner, where this file catches it — proving the full
// throw → reject → rethrow chain, not just an uncaught banner.
int deadAwait() {
    Promise<int> p = Promise();
    int r = await p;              // nothing will ever resolve p
    return r;
}
Worker<int> w = std::spawn(() => deadAwait());
try {
    int got = await w;
    console.writeln("unreachable");
} catch (RuntimeException e) {
    console.writeln("caught: " + e.message);
}
